TY  - JOUR
T1  - Apprentice, Departure, and Demotion: An Examination of the Three Types of CEO–Board Chair Separation
AU  - Krause, Ryan
AU  - Semadeni, Matthew
Y1  - 2012/07/24
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2013/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.0121
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.0121
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 805
EP  - 826
VL  - 56
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Past research has consistently shown that separation of CEO and board chair roles has no systematic effect on firm performance. In this study, we introduce the different forms of such separation: apprentice, departure, and demotion. In a study of Standard & Poor's (S&P) 1500 and Fortune 1000 firms, we find that separation of the two leadership roles positively impacts future firm performance when current performance is poor, but negatively impacts future firm performance when current performance is high. We find that this effect is most dramatic for demotion separations. Finally, we test theory about the permanency of CEO?board chair separation. Our results show that the different types of CEO?board chair separation have very distinct consequences.
AB  - Past research has consistently shown that separation of CEO and board chair roles has no systematic effect on firm performance. In this study, we introduce the different forms of such separation: apprentice, departure, and demotion. In a study of Standard & Poor's (S&P) 1500 and Fortune 1000 firms, we find that separation of the two leadership roles positively impacts future firm performance when current performance is poor, but negatively impacts future firm performance when current performance is high. We find that this effect is most dramatic for demotion separations. Finally, we test theory about the permanency of CEO?board chair separation. Our results show that the different types of CEO?board chair separation have very distinct consequences.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.0121
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amj.2011.0121
Y2  - 2026/04/24
